<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="438" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,790,1573]" pageId="1" pageNumber="438">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,790,816]" pageId="1" pageNumber="438">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Small sized (wing length &lt;
<quantity box="[590,680,790,817]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="1" pageNumber="438" unit="mm" value="1.5">1.5 mm</quantity>
), often dull brown/ grey coloured species; arista usually dorsal, and often in slight indentation subtended by short ventral projection; dorsal postcranium flat; acrostichal setae absent; 5 dorsocentral setae, sometimes 4; two strong medial scutellar setae only; posterior mesonotum distinctly flattened anteriad of scutellum (
<figureCitation box="[402,484,899,925]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1924,1948]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,417,1901]" captionTargetId="figure-134@6.[151,1435,417,1901]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 2. Micromorphus caudatus (Aldrich): a, male habitus, left lateral; b, male postabdomen, left lateral; c, female habitus, dorsal; M. micidus Parent; d, female postabdomen, dorsal; e, male habitus, left lateral; f, male wing, dorsal." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6450985" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6450985/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="438">Fig. 2c</figureCitation>
); legs rather bare of major setae except for distinct anterior preapicals on FII and FIII (
<figureCitation box="[160,241,935,961]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1924,1948]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,417,1901]" captionTargetId="figure-134@6.[151,1435,417,1901]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 2. Micromorphus caudatus (Aldrich): a, male habitus, left lateral; b, male postabdomen, left lateral; c, female habitus, dorsal; M. micidus Parent; d, female postabdomen, dorsal; e, male habitus, left lateral; f, male wing, dorsal." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6450985" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6450985/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="438">Fig. 2a</figureCitation>
), and TII with strong ad seta and weak pd seta near 1/3; hypopygium usually on elongate peduncle that can be exserted (
<figureCitation box="[296,413,971,998]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1859,1883]" captionTargetBox="[162,1430,185,1825]" captionTargetId="figure-29@4.[150,1437,179,1832]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Micromorphus caudatus (Aldrich): a, male postabdomen, ventral; b, male postabdomen, left lateral. M. micidus Parent: c, male postabdomen, left lateral. Legend: cer, cercus; el, epandrial lobe; epand, epandrium; hyp, hypandrium; ph, phallus; st, sternite, tg, tergite; vsur, ventral surstylus. Arrows indicate position of diagnostic setae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6450983" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6450983/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="438">Figs 1a, b</figureCitation>
); male sternite 8 usually with distinct median dorsoventral sclerotized band (
<figureCitation box="[1289,1377,971,997]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1859,1883]" captionTargetBox="[162,1430,185,1825]" captionTargetId="figure-29@4.[150,1437,179,1832]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Micromorphus caudatus (Aldrich): a, male postabdomen, ventral; b, male postabdomen, left lateral. M. micidus Parent: c, male postabdomen, left lateral. Legend: cer, cercus; el, epandrial lobe; epand, epandrium; hyp, hypandrium; ph, phallus; st, sternite, tg, tergite; vsur, ventral surstylus. Arrows indicate position of diagnostic setae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6450983" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6450983/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="438">Figs 1b</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1391,1422,971,998]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1924,1948]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,417,1901]" captionTargetId="figure-134@6.[151,1435,417,1901]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 2. Micromorphus caudatus (Aldrich): a, male habitus, left lateral; b, male postabdomen, left lateral; c, female habitus, dorsal; M. micidus Parent; d, female postabdomen, dorsal; e, male habitus, left lateral; f, male wing, dorsal." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6450985" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6450985/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="438">2b</figureCitation>
); hypopygial foramen left lateral; epandrium subrectangular; females with tergite 9+10 divided into two acanthophorites, each bearing 4 pointed spines or dornen.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="438" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,790,1573]" pageId="1" pageNumber="438">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1079,1105]" pageId="1" pageNumber="438">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mik" authorityYear="1878" box="[323,488,1079,1105]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Micromorphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="438" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[323,488,1079,1105]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="438">Micromorphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
comprises some 32 valid species from all zoogeographic regions except Australasia (
<bibRefCitation author="Wikipedia Contributors" box="[158,490,1115,1141]" pageId="1" pageNumber="438" refId="ref6077" refString="Wikipedia Contributors (2021) Micromorphus. In: Wikipedia, the Free Encyclopedia. Available from: https: // en. wikipedia. org / w / index. php? title = Micromorphus &amp; oldid = 1021996915 (accessed 21 November 2021)" type="url" year="2021">
Wikipedia contributors, 
<date box="[431,490,1115,1141]" pageId="1" pageNumber="438" value="2021-05-07">2021</date>
</bibRefCitation>
, May 7). Its range includes such widely separated locales as 
<collectingCountry box="[1165,1309,1115,1141]" name="South Africa" pageId="1" pageNumber="438">South Africa</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1319,1432,1115,1141]" name="Tajikistan" pageId="1" pageNumber="438">Tajikistan</collectingCountry>
, the 
<collectingCountry box="[192,321,1151,1177]" name="Philippines" pageId="1" pageNumber="438">Philippines</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[332,400,1151,1177]" name="Brazil" pageId="1" pageNumber="438">Brazil</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[455,544,1151,1177]" name="Mexico" pageId="1" pageNumber="438">Mexico</collectingCountry>
. Although the identity of some species based on females only requires reassessment, undoubtedly more species await description. For example, 
<bibRefCitation author="Negrobov, O. P." box="[882,1076,1187,1213]" pageId="1" pageNumber="438" pagination="19 - 26" refId="ref5615" refString="Negrobov, O. P. (2000) Revision of the Palaearctic species of the genus Micromorphu s Mik (Diptera: Dolichopodidae). International Journal of Dipterological Research, 11, 19 - 26." type="journal article" year="2000">Negrobov (2000)</bibRefCitation>
described eight new Palaearctic 
<taxonomicName box="[151,408,1223,1249]" pageId="1" pageNumber="438">
<emphasis box="[151,316,1223,1249]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="438">Micromorphus</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
, with four from 
<collectingCountry box="[590,704,1223,1249]" name="Tajikistan" pageId="1" pageNumber="438">Tajikistan</collectingCountry>
. This suggests the genus as a whole is significantly more diverse, but possibly overlooked because of its small size and the necessity to clear the male postabdomen for accurate identification. Regarding its position in the higher classification of the 
<taxonomicName box="[967,1149,1295,1321]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="438" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Dolichopodidae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mik" authorityYear="1878" box="[1162,1327,1295,1321]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Micromorphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="438" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1162,1327,1295,1321]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="438">Micromorphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been variously placed in the subfamilies 
<taxonomicName authorityName="J.M.Aldrich" authorityYear="1905" box="[549,701,1331,1357]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="438" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Sympycninae">Sympycninae</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Robinson" authorityYear="1970" box="[755,932,1331,1357]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="438" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Peloropeodinae">Peloropeodinae</taxonomicName>
, or is regarded as 
<emphasis box="[1135,1297,1331,1357]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="438">incertae sedis.</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,790,1573]" pageId="1" pageNumber="438">
The male postabdomen provides diagnostic structural, setal and cercal characters that enable accurate species identification (e.g., 
<figureCitation box="[374,488,1403,1429]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1859,1883]" captionTargetBox="[162,1430,185,1825]" captionTargetId="figure-29@4.[150,1437,179,1832]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Micromorphus caudatus (Aldrich): a, male postabdomen, ventral; b, male postabdomen, left lateral. M. micidus Parent: c, male postabdomen, left lateral. Legend: cer, cercus; el, epandrial lobe; epand, epandrium; hyp, hypandrium; ph, phallus; st, sternite, tg, tergite; vsur, ventral surstylus. Arrows indicate position of diagnostic setae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6450983" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6450983/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="438">Figs 1a–b</figureCitation>
, with arrows indicating diagnostic setal positions). Also, it is important to clear the male postabdomen to view the diagnostic structures microscopically, as they may appear obscured in casual macroscopic view (cf. 
<figureCitation box="[365,449,1475,1501]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1859,1883]" captionTargetBox="[162,1430,185,1825]" captionTargetId="figure-29@4.[150,1437,179,1832]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 1. Micromorphus caudatus (Aldrich): a, male postabdomen, ventral; b, male postabdomen, left lateral. M. micidus Parent: c, male postabdomen, left lateral. Legend: cer, cercus; el, epandrial lobe; epand, epandrium; hyp, hypandrium; ph, phallus; st, sternite, tg, tergite; vsur, ventral surstylus. Arrows indicate position of diagnostic setae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6450983" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6450983/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="438">Figs 1a</figureCitation>
and 
<figureCitation box="[506,537,1475,1502]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1924,1948]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,417,1901]" captionTargetId="figure-134@6.[151,1435,417,1901]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 2. Micromorphus caudatus (Aldrich): a, male habitus, left lateral; b, male postabdomen, left lateral; c, female habitus, dorsal; M. micidus Parent; d, female postabdomen, dorsal; e, male habitus, left lateral; f, male wing, dorsal." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6450985" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6450985/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="438">2b</figureCitation>
). Species in the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mik" authorityYear="1878" box="[801,966,1475,1501]" class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Micromorphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="438" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[801,966,1475,1501]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="438">Micromorphus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are rather bare of distinctive leg setation and generally lack diagnostic male secondary sexual characters, although two Afrotropical species have flattened tarsomeres on male legs I and II (
<bibRefCitation author="Grichanov, I. Ya." box="[525,713,1547,1573]" pageId="1" pageNumber="438" pagination="607 - 611" refId="ref5503" refString="Grichanov, I. Ya. (2013) Afrotropical species of the genus Micromorphus Mik, 1878 (Diptera, Dolichopodidae). Euroasian Entomological Journal, 12, 607 - 611." type="journal article" year="2013">Grichanov 2013</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
